page_description: Tribal Newspaper, based in Toppenish Washington.
message: Ward earns salmon recovery award WENACHEE, Wash. ‚Äì The Upper Columbia Salmon Recovery Board (UCSRB) is honored to award Paul Ward, long-time UCSRB Director and Yakama Nation Fisheries Manager, with the Esther Stefaniw Memorial Award. The award is reserved for those who make substantial contributions to restoring salmon and steelhead in the Upper Columbia region, an Oct. 5 UCSRB press release said. Ward served as a UCSRB Director for two decades, working to build meaningful, lasting relationships with diverse partners and to find solutions that worked for all parties. He understood, as did then Chelan County Commissioner Esther Stefaniw, that a solid foundation of collaboration between stakeholders would be critical to the long journey of salmon recovery. Ward navigated many challenging issues over the years, with a keen ability to find consensus among partners, the release said. His innovative thinking launched many important initiatives including the North Central Washington Forest Health Collaborative. In Ward‚Äôs tenure at UCSRB, he mentored many individuals who will continue to champion the ‚ÄúWashington Way‚Äù of salmon recovery ‚Äì voluntary implementation, strong tribal and local leadership and partnerships among all stakeholders, from the landowners to the U.S. Legislature. UCSRB wished Ward well in his new role as the Intergovernmental Affairs Director of the Columbia River Inter-Tribal Fish Commission and look forward to our continued work with him in that capacity. On the Net: UCSRB Upper Columbia Spring Chinook Salmon and Steelhead Recovery Plan, ucsrb.org

page_description: Tribal Newspaper, based in Toppenish Washington.
message: YVC support service is the hand needed by Jaren Wallulatum Grant bolsters support for first-generation, low-income students YAKIMA, Wash. ‚Äì After Jaren Wallulatum graduated from high school in 2014 he enrolled at a college in his home state of Oregon, uncertain what career path to pursue ‚Äì and like many first-generation students, he wasn‚Äôt sure where to go for support as he started his college experience. ‚ÄúFor myself, it was difficult being new to higher education,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt know where to look for the resources I needed to succeed.‚Äù Wallulatum would transfer to another college before leaving school to enter the workforce and moving to Washington. Two years later, he gave college another try ‚Äì only this time with the support he had earlier lacked. He used Yakima Valley College‚Äôs TRIO Student Support Services, a federally-funded program that provides low-income and first-generation students with academic support services such as tutoring, assistance with education plans, personal and career counseling, book loans and more, an Oct. 19 YVC press release said. Wallulatum graduated from YVC in 2019 and is now an economics and public policy major at Central Washington University in Ellensburg, Wash. ‚ÄúFinding TRIO made a huge difference for me in navigating the higher education system,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúIt helped build a network of peers, instructors and college staff who I can reach out to for help.‚Äù The YVC program will be able to extend the program for five years after receiving a $1.8 million grant from the U.S. Department of Education. TRIO helps YVC students overcome class, social and cultural barriers to higher education, said the program‚Äôs director, Dustin Shattuck. ‚ÄúTRIO works because it serves a population ‚Äì first-generation, low-income students ‚Äì who don‚Äôt usually know how to navigate college,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúA lot of these students have been through a lot of adversity, but when they have access to some of these resources to succeed, you really see them blossom.‚Äù In each of the next five years, 200 students will be supported through YVC‚Äôs TRIO program, with individual students being served from one to three years depending on their academic pathway, the release said. Financial aid programs help students overcome financial barriers to accessing higher education and Shattuck said TRIO‚Äôs services focus on empowering students to succeed in their educational journeys. For example, students participate in a learning community from the beginning of their time at YVC in order to build networks of peer support. They also have coursework supplemented with advising and mentoring aligned with their career goals, and the college offers workshops and field trips on financial literacy, financial aid and scholarship applications, career and worksite awareness, cultural awareness and planning for transfer. ‚ÄúOur program focuses on engaging with students around their career intentions and the bridge that education plays in attaining these careers,‚Äù Shattuck said. At the end of Wallulatum‚Äôs first year at YVC, he and handful of other students in the program were approached by their advisor about starting a peer mentoring and leadership program. ‚ÄúThat was an experience that really helped build our leadership and professional skills because we were in charge of planning a lot of activities for our peers and their growth,‚Äù he said. Following that leadership experience, Wallulatum would go on to serve as YVC Student Council President. He is scheduled to complete his bachelor‚Äôs degree in 2022 and then enter CWU‚Äôs graduate program in cultural and environmental resources management. Wallulatum, who grew up on Warm Springs Reservation, is interested in studying how his tribe and other tribes can maximize the resources on reservations for the benefit of those living on them. ‚ÄúTRIO helps inspire students to continue to go further in education and in their careers,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúThose connections you make are life and career connections you can continue to reach out to. There are still friends I made who I talk to on a daily basis and I know that I can reach out to them anytime for assistance and I know that I can reach out to the faculty anytime in the future.‚Äù On the Net: TRIO Student Support Services, yvcc.edu/services/sss/:=:https://www.yvcc.edu/services/sss/

message: First Nations awards Changing Native Food Economies awards LONGMONT, Colo. ‚Äì First Nations Development Institute announced Oct. 14, the awarding of seven grants to help Native-led organizations improve their community-based food sovereignty efforts for the benefit of Native children and families. The grants will also be used to address issues of food insecurity, jobs, household budgets, cultural connections, and the sustainable use of natural resources, a press release said. The 2020 round of seven grantees will each received $40,000 to support their programs and services. The Swinomish Indian Tribal Community will build on work to increase access to fresh fruits and vegetables by focusing on sustaining long-term access by developing partnerships with local produce growers, bolstering the Swinomish community‚Äôs 13 Moons garden, and offering additional classes on harvesting, preparing, and preserving Swinomish traditional foods. The Feed Seven Generations, Enumclaw, Wash. will leverage partnerships with tribal farmers, fishermen and tribal members to increase access to and control of local tribal food systems, create economic opportunities for producers/fisherman, improve health outcomes, and create a model for tribes in Washington to increase access to traditional and culturally significant foods. The Center Pole, Garryowen, Mont. will increase traditional and healthy food access in their tribal community, the Crow Reservation, by creating a healthy foods hub that will serve and distribute healthy and traditional foods. The project will leverage data collected via their community food sovereignty assessment and will help in retaining Indigenous food knowledge and supporting healthy eating habits that will lead to better health outcomes. Fast Blackfeet, Browning, Mont. The O‚Äôyo‚Äôp‚Äô On Wheels Program will create a part-time position to service eight outlying communities on the Blackfeet Reservation with regularly scheduled food deliveries. The program will utilize Fast Blackfeet‚Äôs existing client database to reach families and support a consistent delivery schedule, resulting in increased participation in the food program. Fort Belknap Community Economic Development Corporation in Harlem, Mont. will increase the tribal community‚Äôs access to the Red Paint Creek Trading Post & Pantry by upgrading their distribution vehicle and trailer so they can transport additional food pallets. This will enable families to stretch monthly food dollars and purchase more food and critical items locally, supporting the community-owned grocery cooperative, food pantry, and commercial kitchen. The Spirit Lake Tribe, Fort Totten, N.D. will develop the Spirit Lake Tribe‚Äôs Community Farmers‚Äô Market to support and promote community engagement in food systems and Native-led entrepreneurial endeavors in agriculture while increasing the tribal community‚Äôs access to locally grown fresh produce and traditional foods. It will also support continued expansion of their existing indoor gardening, aquaponics, and hydroponics operations. The Standing Rock Sioux Tribe‚Äôs Traditional Foods Pathway Program, Fort Yates, N.D. will create a healthy food system for the tribe. The program will incorporate traditional foods and food practices and will engage other tribal programs, tribal members, and local partnerships as the Tribe leverages, retains, and increases its traditional knowledge. The grants are made possible through First Nations‚Äô Changing Native Food Economies grant program, which is part of the organization‚Äôs Native Agriculture & Food Systems Initiative. The program, which supports two of the overarching goals related to food sovereignty and asset building and the development of strong, diverse, and resilient tribal economies, is supported with funding from the Northwest Area Foundation.

message: YVC offers virtual information sessions to learn more about B.S. programs YAKIMA, Wash. ‚Äì Yakima Valley College will offer two virtual information sessions for the Bachelor of Applied Science Degree programs, an Oct. 14 press release said. The programs are designed for prospective students who have earned an applied associate‚Äôs degree and need a pathway to pursue a bachelor‚Äôs degree. Sessions will be held on Wednesday, October 28, 2020 at 12:30 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. A Bachelor of Applied Science in Business Management BASM provides curriculum that prepares students for management positions in a variety of industries. Subjects include financial management, marketing, project management and more. Courses are offered during the evening in a hybrid format (combination of in-person and online coursework). A Bachelor of Applied Science in Information Technology Networking - System Administration prepares students for occupations in system administration such as network administrator, database administrator, computer system analyst and more. This degree broadens a student‚Äôs foundational knowledge in information technology, specifically system administration ‚Äî in addition to general education, theory, advanced technical and professional skills, and integrated collaborative learning. The Bachelor of Applied Science Degree in Teacher Education prepares individuals for a Washington State Teacher Certificate in Elementary Education (K-8), with additional optional endorsements in English Language Learner and Early Childhood Education. Candidates complete an intensive residency experience in a local school that requires hands-on work in classrooms under the guidance of a mentor teacher and field supervisor. The Bachelor or Applied Science in Dental Hygiene prepares accepted candidates to recognize, treat and prevent oral diseases as a Registered Dental Hygienist. Curriculum consists of six quarters of professional education and clinical experience preceded by 65 college-level credits in specific prerequisite courses. Dental Hygiene is the only BAS program at YVC that does not require completion of an AAS or equivalent to apply. YVC students save an average of more than $12,000 per year compared to first-year students at a public university and over $51,000 compared to freshman at a private university in Washington State, the YVC press release said On the Net: Additional information, yvcc.edu/bachelors:=:https://www.yvcc.edu/academics/bachelor-degree/ Virtual sessions via Zoom, https://us02web.zoom.us/j/87941022062

message: WDFW plans controlled burn on Oak Creek Wildlife Area SPOKANE ‚Äì The Washington Department of Fish & Wildlife will do controlled burns to restore habitat on the Oak Creek Wildlife Area in Yakima County starting as early as next week, an Oct. 1 press release said. With cooler temperatures and higher humidity reducing wildfire danger, WDFW lifted fire restrictions on most department-managed lands on Oct. 1., allowing prescribed burns to move forward, dependent on weather conditions. Matt Eberlein, WDFW Prescribed Fire Program Manager, says burn crews will be extremely cognizant of wildfire conditions. Fire activity will also be limited to areas with lower smoke impact to the public and communities, and take into consideration upcoming hunting seasons. ‚ÄúBurning activities could continue into October but with the intent to be completed prior to the opening of modern firearm elk season,‚Äù he said. The area to be burned is a total of 120 acres approximately 10 miles up the Oak Creek Road/drainage. Portions of the wildlife area may be closed during the controlled burns, and people may see smoke for a couple hours after the burns. WDFW uses controlled burns to reduce uncharacteristic fuels that would otherwise burn hotter than they are adapted to withstand in wildfires. Prescribed fire also destroys invasive plants, improves wildlife habitat, and rejuvenates existing foliage. ‚ÄúFire is a natural part of both forest and grassland ecology and controlled fire can be an extremely effective tool for foresters,‚Äù said Eberlein. This proactive work is part of the state‚Äôs 20-year Forest Health strategy and is intended to support the ability of the landscape to survive and thrive when wildfires occur. WDFW lands are generally located between higher elevation federally managed forests and lower elevation populated areas, making their fire resilience critical for community safety in addition to the integrity of the forested habitats for fish and wildlife. Signs warning wildlife area users will be posted in burn areas. Additional burns could be announced as fall progresses, depending on conditions.

message: Nathan Apodaca: Everyone‚Äôs new cousin By ALIYAH CHAVEZ Indian Country Today ‚ÄúIs 100 likes good?‚Äù Nathan Apodaca asked his daughter after uploading his first set of TikTok videos two years ago. Fast-forward, and the Northern Arapaho TikToker has become a beacon of hope and positive vibes after his viral video skateboarding to Fleetwood Mac‚Äôs ‚ÄúDreams‚Äù was seen by millions. Since uploading it at the end of September, he has received 8 million likes on TikTok and counting. The throwback song garnered its best-ever weekly streams. And the Ocean Spray juice company gifted Apodaca a truck loaded with crates of juice. Many in Indian Country were quick to notice the tattoo on the back of Apodaca‚Äôs head, which depicts a pair of feathers. They‚Äôre now excited to cheer him on. In an interview with Indian Country Today, Apodaca, 37, said the feathers represent his mother‚Äôs side of the family. She is Northern Arapaho and grew up on the Wind River Reservation in Wyoming. While Apodaca grew up in Idaho Falls, Idaho, he says he remembers trips to the Wind River rez. The reservation is home to two tribal nations, the Eastern Shoshone and Northern Arapaho. ‚ÄúWe would go visit them [family] all the time in the past,‚Äù Apodaca said. The top half of the feathers depict a Northern Arapaho flag. He hopes to get another tattoo on the other side of his head to represent his dad‚Äôs side, which is Mexican. ‚ÄúI just want to say to the Indigenous people out there, stay strong. I know times are tough right now, especially on the rez,‚Äù Apodaca said. Prior to his viral video, Apodaca had been producing TikTok content with the help of his daughters, Angelia and Makyla. His first viral video, posted last year, hit 1.2 million views in two days. The video showed him dancing to ‚ÄúGet Up‚Äù by Ciara. From that video, he built his following until he had more than 136,000 followers. Shortly after, he decided to launch a line of shirts and beanies he embroidered himself. Now Apodaca has a line of merchandise including sweatshirts and T-shirts that feature a screenshot of him skating with juice. Public figures including musicians, actors and influencers have shared Apodaca‚Äôs latest viral video. When asked which figure has meant the most to him, Apodaca said Bizzy Bone, a rapper with Bone Thugs-N-Harmony, as well as Jay and Silent Bob. He says his social media platforms have garnered so many messages that it‚Äôs been hard to keep up. He recently signed with a talent agency and hired a manager. ‚ÄúAs soon as I signed with her [Gina, his manager], she just took off. It‚Äôs been crazy. And she‚Äôs getting excited like no other,‚Äù Apodaca said. In the meantime, Apodaca says he is getting used to life after going viral. He plans to continue producing content and being himself, which is what bolstered his popularity to begin with. He also says he will continue to encourage Natives on TikTok. ‚ÄúTo the Indigenous people, get out there and make videos, go do what you want because I‚Äôve been seeing a lot of Natives on TikTok just blowing up. Follow your fellow Natives, follow each other,‚Äù Apodaca said. ‚ÄúBe one with each other. One nation, we rise.‚Äù Aliyah Chavez, Kewa Pueblo, is a reporter-producer at Indian Country Today. Follow her on Twitter: @aliyachavez or email achevez@indiancountrytoday.com . Indian Country Today is a non-profit news organization. Will you support our work? All of our content is free. There are no subscriptions or costs. And we have hired more Native journalists in the past year than any news organization ‚îÄ and with your help we will continue to grow and create career paths for our people. Support ICT for as little as $10.

message: Tribal news deserts thrive when citizens‚Äô media lack access to public records Freedom of Information could enhance quality of life for Native communities. By Jodi Rave Spotted Bear I learned the importance of sharing information with readers during more than a decade I reported on American Indian issues for Lee Enterprises. I covered national news then. Now I‚Äôm doing my best to report on local news in my home community on the Fort Berthold Reservation in North Dakota. It‚Äôs particularly difficult to gather facts in this news desert unlike other news deserts where Freedom of Information, or FOI, and Sunshine laws exist. The First Amendment and the Indian Civil Rights Act lack agency on Native lands held in trust by the U.S. Interior Department. That‚Äôs because tribal sovereignty often trumps citizen rights. I willingly once helped outside reporters who arrived at Fort Berthold, homeland of the Mandan, Hidatsa and Arikara Nation of the Three Affiliated Tribes. I used to think any type of news is better than no news. But, when parachute journalists, Native or non-Native, land for a minute, then write hit-and-miss stories, they often do more harm. I often wonder if they have fact checkers in their publications. Meanwhile, we need local stories told on a regular basis. The absence, however, of FOI and Sunshine laws, and open meetings held in the light of the sun, creates a challenge when trying to accurately report on tribal governments. The void of media laws ‚Äî and journalism programs at tribal colleges ‚Äî helps explain why I live in a news desert, ‚Äúa community, either rural or urban, with limited access to the sort of credible and comprehensive news and information that feeds democracy at the grassroots level,‚Äù as defined by the Center for Innovation and Sustainability in Local Media. As a 2021‚Äì2022 John S. Knight Community Impact Fellow, I have a team of fellows, advisors and resources to help me explore options to building a local news ecosystem. My Stanford University fellowship affords access to research a number of issues, including how a Freedom of Information Act, or FOIA, code backed by a constitutional amendment could benefit tribal citizens. As the founder and director of the Indigenous Media Freedom Alliance, I guide the organization to advocate for press freedom and the growth of independent news operations. Here‚Äôs a Native media report I wrote for the Democracy Fund. The IMFA, which is based in Twin Buttes, N.D., publishes on buffalosfire.com. Given FOI tools, tribal citizens, Native journalists and local media could access tribal government records. In turn, the community could take action to increase the quality of life for themselves and their families. If we had better informed communities our social, political, environmental and economic well-being would improve, and American Indians wouldn‚Äôt be perennial poverty stars of the mainstream media. How many news stories have we read or viewed on ‚Äúpoverty, alcohol and drug abuse run amok‚Äù in Native communities? The go-to location for that story typically is the Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota. Yes, we also see widespread stories on government mismanagement. While tribal business activities deserve the light of day, more often than not, they remain masked. Those stories ‚Äî like MHA Nation payday lending operations ‚Äî often aren‚Äôt reported until they end up in federal court. Corruption could be avoided if there was more accountability and transparency in tribal government. A federal grand jury investigation on tribal corruption at the Fort Berthold Reservation ended in 2020. The Justice Department later issued three indictments centered on bribery and kickbacks. Sources close to the issue expect more indictments to be forthcoming. Tribal leaders routinely use tribal sovereignty and sovereign immunity to shield the sunlight. I‚Äôve seen MHA Nation Tribal Business Council ‚Äî the governing body of the Three Affiliated Tribes ‚Äî agendas where the council meets with oil companies in closed sessions. As citizens, we are not informed how our tribal councilmen annually spend multi-million-dollar community budgets. Most of that money comes from oil revenue derived from extraction of natural resources on tribal and individual lands held in trust by the Interior Department. The local Bureau of Indian Affairs stands guard over information related to tribal and individual lands. I‚Äôm routinely told I am not a party of interest to reservation land records. But oil companies freely can access the information. In addition, our community members are not informed of the environmental dangers posed by the hydraulic fracking industry. The lack of FOI laws on tribal lands is not unique to my tribe, the Mandan, Hidatsa and Arikara Nation. Out of 574 federally-recognized tribes in the United States, I am limited on best examples of FOIA or public records codes, but the Cherokee, Osage and Muscogee nations of Oklahoma stand tall. Here‚Äôs the Muscogee 16-page code, (truncated)

message: Fishers on a rainy day In early May tribal fishers were busy at Drano Lake getting ready to fish either by boat or casting their reels into the lake. It was a rainy day which is good because fish think the raindrops are insects and get near the top of the water and easier for fishers to catch. Llewellyn Sampson casts his pole near The Dalles Dam where he and two other fishers were spending the day. He caught eight fish on May 9 and one May12. YNR photos by Carol Craig.

message: Five artists announced By CAROL CRAIG Yakama Nation Review TOPPENISH, Wash.‚ÄîYakama tribal artists sent their artwork entries to Yakamart with the top three chosen for the Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women (MMIW) poster. One artist, Karan Matta, received First Place for her ‚ÄúLeave No Child Behind,‚Äù poster. Her drawing was the only entry and she took home $500. Her brightly colored orange drawing has silhouettes of seven children‚Äôs back sitting down. One tiny child leans against another. Matta said she used pencil, colored pencil, and a black Sharpie. ‚ÄúI chose seven children's silhouettes as representing the seven days of the week. The seven birds represent the children's spirits being lifted up after repatriation,‚Äù she said. The MMIW First Place winner is Corey Bradley and he received $500. The artwork has a red background with a woman‚Äôs eyes and a teardrop. An eagle is flying past her. Second Place winner for the MMIW poster is Terrance Paul, who received $300. It has the letters MMIW run across a page with the feather serving as the letter ‚ÄòI.‚Äô Handprints go across the letters and the letter ‚ÄòW‚Äô has three backs of women in red dresses. Third Place has the title ‚ÄòNo more stolen sisters‚Äô at the top with the woman facing sideways and tears down her face and is wearing a red feather earring. A red handprint is in the background. Viola Wallulatum received $200. Yakamart staff chose the winners and will now decide where to place each blown up poster size piece of artwork throughout the store. One of the drawings may be on the entry doorway to Yakamart. Below--Is the Leave No Child Behind, first place, Karan Matta, First Place for MMIW--Corey Bradley; Second Place--Terrence Paul and Third Place for MMIW--Viola Wallulatum.

message: Tribal member lands dual role in movie By RYAN CRAIG KYNR News TOPPENISH, Wash. ‚Äì A Yakama tribal member landed a dual role in a movie titled All Sorts. Anthony Hernandez, Jr., 39 and of Toppenish, had two small acting roles in the comedy/drama film. Hernandez remembered the auditions taking place sometime in late 2017 for the film. ‚ÄúI wasn‚Äôt really into it at the time,‚Äù he said when remembering first hearing about the movie auditions. Hernandez said it was a girlfriend he had ‚Äì at the time ‚Äì who told him about the movie auditions. ‚ÄúIt was more to be supportive of her,‚Äù he said. After his then girlfriend printed out scripts of the lead male roles and gave them to him, Hernandez studied the lines and auditioned for the three lead male roles. The auditions were held in Granger, Wash. While Hernandez didn‚Äôt land any of the main roles, the director liked his tattoos, Hernandez said and offered him a role as a doorman in All Sorts. The writer and director of All Sorts, J. Rick Castaneda, is originally from Granger, Wash. and has a degree in filmmaking from University of Southern California in Los Angeles, Calif. All Sorts is his second feature film that he‚Äôs written and directed and is described as a comedy/drama. The film also has a theme of a romance. The short synopsis on the films website reads: ‚ÄúA lonely data clerk finds his way into the magical world of championship folder filing.‚Äù Hernandez said he enjoyed working with Castaneda. ‚ÄúHe gives great direction,‚Äù Hernandez said of the writer and director. ‚ÄúHe was really easy to work with and get along with.‚Äù For Hernandez, the experience on the set of the movie was one he enjoyed. ‚ÄúIt was pretty cool,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúIt was a legit movie set.‚Äù Hernandez said that while he had only a few speaking lines in the film, he was still required to put in full days of work to get his part done. ‚ÄúEven for my small role, I still had to wear makeup,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI still had to rehearse my lines. Just say my part over and over. It was really repetitive.‚Äù The final sequence of All Sorts was filmed at the AJ Strom Gymnasium at the Toppenish Middle School. The climatic finale was full of humor, suspense and even some action. In the final ‚Äúshowdown‚Äù of speed filers, Hernandez played the role of a referee. The final filing competition was held inside of a boxing ring. There were even high school marching bands on hand from Grandview and Granger as well as many extras in the crowd from the Yakima Valley community. Besides having two small roles in the film, Hernandez was also involved in the movie as a driver. Hernandez, along with his niece, Alyssa Morales who was the assistant driver, drove a truck while the main characters rode in their car and acted out their parts. ‚ÄúSo, all the scenes where you see them driving, they‚Äôre actually being pulled by a tow truck,‚Äù Hernandez shared. ‚ÄúTheir car is on a trailer and they‚Äôre being pulled and I‚Äôm driving the truck pulling them,‚Äù he said. Hernandez said that overall, he was thankful to have been a part of the film All Sorts. It inspired him to do more things he said. He‚Äôs started writing more ideas and scripts of his own and has been working with other local artists and actors on projects locally. Outside of his full time job, Hernandez said he also enjoys performing as a standup comedian. He began performing comedy in 2012. He is also a co-host to his own podcast called ‚ÄúKilling Time with Anthony & Brian.‚Äù He and his co-host began the podcast around a year ago and they've currently hosted and recorded around 107 episodes. Their topics on the podcast range from current events to sharing old stories from their lives to hosting other comedians as guests. ‚ÄúKilling Time‚Äù podcast is on Spotify and Apple as well as the website killingtime.space

message: Yakama Cultural Center hosts healthy drive-by By RONNIE WASHINES Yakama Nation Review TOPPENISH, Wash. ‚Äì Several Yakama Nation programs and services were part of a motorized health promotion event Sept. 29 around the Yakama Nation Cultural Heritage Center. Cars, trucks and vans lined the roadway leading up to the event, which started at 11 a.m. Several sponsored stations were set up, including handing out Yakama Nation insignia health facemasks, suicide prevention information, safe health information, children reading material, program service contact information, voter registration, 2020 Census incentive booth ‚Äì and free hotdogs. About 50 volunteers from several offices helped with the event. The car line reached back about one-third of a mile onto Spil-Yii Loop and Buster and Fort roads. Those who could prove completing the 2020 census could be entered into a drawing that had a top prize of a big screen television and video game consoles. The hot dogs were supplied by the Soup-N-Dog concession trailer. No figures were provided on how many people came through, but the event ran out of facemasks handouts. Below--Chip Strom shares flyers with those who did the drive-by. Nacona Abras and Strom greet community members upon arriving to the healthy drive-by. A hot dog mascot waves to people as they receive their hotdogs and chips from Soup-R-Dog concession trailers. YNR photos by Ryan Craig.

message: Tribal behavioral health program holds ‚ÄòKuthla‚Äô mask drawing TOPPENISH, Wash. ‚Äì The Yakama Nation Behavioral Health Services Program sponsored a Kuthla Mask Give Away Oct. 14. The YNBHSP coordinated the drawing by Care Navigator Chestina Dominguez in honor of October 12 being Indigenous Peoples Day. To enter the drawing, people responded via email to Dominguez on what they do in the way of self-care. ‚ÄúWe had over 90 people who shared what they do for self-care,‚Äù she said in an Oct. 14 email announcement. ‚ÄúPlease keep doing your self-care.‚Äù Fionna John, Kathleen Strong and Angus Hudson all won special Kuthla designed masks by Nerdy Creations. Dominguez said people could contact her at (509) 865-2266 to find out about YNBHSP services. ‚ÄúWe have to take of ourselves before we can take care of our families, friends, and work duties,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúWith the success of this giveaway, I think I‚Äôll do more in the future. Naktkwninsha (take care of yourself) relatives!‚Äù The YNBHSP Office is located at 217 S. Toppenish Ave. in downtown Toppenish.

page_description: Tribal Newspaper, based in Toppenish Washington.
message: Yakama Nation Fisheries‚Äô Lee Carlson earns Esther Stefaniw Award WENATCHEE, Wash. ‚Äì The Upper Columbia Salmon Recovery Board (UCSRB) awarded Lee Carlson, Yakama Nation Fisheries, with the Esther Stefaniw Memorial Award. The award is presented to those who contribute to restoring salmon, steelhead and other at-risk species through collaborative, economically sensitive efforts. ‚ÄúThis is an award that means quite a bit to me since I had the chance to work with Esther during the initial days of salmon recovery in the Upper Columbia. Ester really was the ‚ÄòEnergizer Bunny‚Äô that got things rolling for the creation of collaborative recovery work,‚Äù Carlson said in a press release. Lee played a foundational role in salmon and steelhead recovery in the Upper Columbia over the past two decades, most notably helping to form the UCSRB, draft the Upper Columbia Spring Chinook Salmon and Steelhead Recovery Plan and establish the regional framework for the plan‚Äôs implementation. In the early days, he served as UCSRB staff when UCSRB barely had any other staff, the Oct. 5 press release said. ‚ÄúAs Recovery Plan implementation began, he continued to help address issues as they arose, always offering a well-thought-out opinion to focus efforts in a positive direction for improvement,‚Äù the UCSRB release state. ‚ÄúLee never left anyone guessing where he stood on an issue ‚Äì though sometimes one did have to ascertain when he was joking and displaying his infamous dry-witted humor!‚Äù On the Net: UCSRB and the Upper Columbia Spring Chinook Salmon and Steelhead Recovery Plan, ucsrb.org.

page_description: Tribal Newspaper, based in Toppenish Washington.
message: NMAI to open Native American Veterans Memorial WASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äì The National Museum of the American Indian will open the new National Native American Veterans Memorial Nov. 11, a museum press release said. The event has a short virtual message to honor the service and sacrifice of Native veterans and their families. The message will be on both the museum‚Äôs website and its YouTube channel, said NMAI Director Kevin Gover. ‚ÄúThe National Native American Veterans Memorial will serve as a reminder to the nation and the world of the service and sacrifice of Native American, Alaska Native and Native Hawaiian veterans,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúNative Americans have always answered the call to serve, and this memorial is a fitting tribute to their patriotism and deep commitment to this country.‚Äù The design features an elevated stainless steel circle resting on a carved stone drum. It also incorporates water for sacred ceremonies, benches for gatherings and four lances where veterans, family members, tribal leaders and others can tie cloths for prayers and healing. The memorial, which sits on the grounds of the museum, was commissioned by Congress to give ‚Äúall Americans the opportunity to learn of the proud and courageous tradition of service of Native Americans in the Armed Forces of the United States.‚Äù The memorial design is by Harvey Pratt ‚Äì Cheyenne and Arapaho tribes in Oklahoma ‚Äì a multimedia artist, retired forensic artist and Marine Corps Vietnam veteran. Major support for the National Native American Veterans Memorial has been provided by the Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes; Chickasaw Nation; Margaret A. Cargill Philanthropies; Poarch Band of Creek Indians; San Manuel Band of Mission Indians; and Shakopee Mdewakanton Sioux Community. The memorial has also been widely supported by tribal governments and tribal veterans organizations. More than 85 tribes, individuals, corporations and other organizations have contributed to the memorial. ‚ÄòWhy We Serve‚Äô To coincide with the completion of the memorial, the museum published Why We Serve: Native Americans in the United States Armed Forces, a 240-page book that commemorates the history of Native American military service. Native Americans serve in the military at one of the highest rates of any ethnic group, and the book explores the many reasons why ‚Äì from love of home to the expression of warrior traditions. The book is co-authored by Alexandra Harris and Mark Hirsch, senior editor and historian, respectively, at the National Museum of the American Indian. A virtual discussion with Harris about identity and the warrior stereotype of Native people serving in the military, as well as actual traditions of peace and war within American Indian communities will take place at noon EST, Nov. 12. Registering details for the Zoom event is at AmericanIndian.si.edu . Educational Module The Native Words, Native Warriors museum module is part of the museum‚Äôs Native Knowledge 360 degree educational initiative, honors the legacy of Native Code Talkers who created secret military communications based on their languages. Their efforts significantly aided Allied victories during World Wars I and II. Vets‚Äô History Project The Library of Congress‚Äô American Folklife Center collects, preserves and makes accessible the personal accounts of American war veterans so future generations may hear their stories and better understand the realities of war. In partnership with the museum, the Veterans‚Äô History Project is preserving the stories of Native men and women who have served in the military through interviews, correspondence and photographs.

message: OUT OF OUR MAILBAG Yakima County residents enjoy Yakima safely REVIEW: As a community, Yakima has worked diligently to follow the public health recommendations and we have seen our cases drop significantly over the past several months. For this reason, we have been able to slowly re-open businesses and even begin to plan for in-person learning. We all must remember that as businesses and other activities slowly re-open, this not because the COVID-19 pandemic is ‚Äúover.‚Äù ‚Äì this is being done because our metrics show that our community has been taking public health recommendations seriously. We continue to see our community members practice social distancing of at least 6 feet, wearing masks in public, keeping their social circle small, conducting activities outdoors when possible rather than indoors, and striving to take care of one another. Unfortunately, there are conflicting messages currently circulating that we can all ‚Äúgo back to normal,‚Äù and this is unfortunately not true. There are plenty of examples demonstrating how quickly COVID-19 can resurge in a community when public health recommendations are not followed. Let‚Äôs continue to do what we have been doing ‚Äì it‚Äôs been working. We went from being the worst in the state and across the West Coast to being a model of what we can be accomplished when we all work together. If we mistakenly believe that we have ‚Äúbeaten‚Äù COVID-19, before a vaccine is readily available ‚Äì we will be on track to go back to where we used to be. As we all begin to revisit our favorite restaurants, enjoy more time together outdoors, and enjoy the other additional activities now permitted in our current phase of the Safe Start Plan, please remember the following to make an educated decision on what risk you are willing to take for yourself and your community: ‚Ä¢ If you are feeling sick - stay home. Reschedule your plans or opt for a web-based get-together like ZOOM or Face Time. ‚Ä¢ Continue to wear your mask in public places and when you are unable to maintain 6 feet of physical distance from others not in your household. ‚Ä¢ Frequently wash your hands for 20 seconds and have hand sanitizer available when going to public places or enjoying the outdoors. ‚Ä¢ Enjoy outdoor gatherings or celebrations with 5 or fewer people outside of your home per week. Remember to wear a mask and wash your hands frequently when gathering with others. ‚Ä¢ Set up children‚Äôs activities that do not require physical contact like going for a walk, riding bikes, jumping rope, or coloring. ‚Ä¢ Call your favorite restaurant, winery, or brewery ahead of time to see if reservations are required and to be aware of indoor seating capacity. If weather permits, choose outdoor seating instead. If the capacity has been reached, whether its enforced or not, considering going elsewhere where the risk is lower. ‚Ä¢ Continue to seek updated information and guidance from objective sources such as the Yakima Health District and the Washington State Department of Health ‚Äì other sources may not present the full information needed to accurately judge risk in the community, including the measures of community safety used by our state public health experts to determine our readiness to move forward. We can and should enjoy Yakima, by following the safety precautions to ensure we can continue to see further declines in our numbers and move towards a path of further reopening. Remember, more people = more risk, indoor is higher risk than outdoor, and less space is higher risk than more space. ‚Äì Yakima County Health Office

message: Nevada dam changes give rare trout new life 115 years later By SCOTT SONNER Associated Press WADSWORTH, Nev. (AP) ‚Äì U.S. and tribal officials are celebrating completion of a $34 million fish bypass system at a Nevada dam that will allow a threatened trout species to return to some of its native spawning grounds for the first time in more than a century. Construction of the side channel with fish-friendly screens is a major step toward someday enabling Lahontan cutthroat trout to make the same 100-mile journey ‚Äì upstream from a desert lake on tribal land northeast of Reno to Lake Tahoe atop the Sierra ‚Äì that they did before the dam was built in 1905. ‚ÄúThis is a great day for conservation,‚Äù said Paul Souza, the regional director of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service who said it wouldn‚Äôt have been possible without support from the Pyramid Lake Paiute Tribe. ‚ÄúThis is an iconic species. This project is going to help get it home,‚Äù he said at a Sept. 30 ceremony at Derby Dam on the Truckee River 20 miles east of Reno. The U.S. Bureau of Reclamation began reconfiguring the dam just a year ago in partnership with the USFWS, Pyramid Lake Paiute Tribe and Farmers Conservation Alliance, a nonprofit group that developed the screens. Brenda Burman, head of the bureau, said the quick work combined the alliance‚Äôs innovative technology with the service‚Äôs biological experience and the bureau‚Äôs engineering and construction expertise. ‚ÄúAnd in the background, pushing and making sure this all happened, we had the relentlessness of the Pyramid Lake Paiute Tribe to recover the fish that they hold sacred,‚Äù she said. The largest trout in North America, Lahontan cutthroats grew as big as 60 pounds when they climbed 2,500 feet through mountain river canyons to Lake Tahoe on the California-Nevada line, elevation 6,228 feet. In recent years, they‚Äôve made their way several miles upstream from Pyramid Lake but haven‚Äôt been able to get past the 30-foot-high dam. Commissioned by President Theodore Roosevelt, the dam was part of the first major irrigation system established in the West to ‚Äúhelp make the desert bloom,‚Äù diverting water to farmers and ranchers in a region where only about 5 inches of rain falls annually. The new bypass houses an 80-foot-wide, 390-foot-long horizontal fish screen ‚Äì actually a metal plate with slots that pushes water down through the water system while sending the fish and other debris through the side channel. The Farmers Irrigation District of Hood River, Oregon, first developed the design after severe flooding in 1996. The district licensed the patent to the alliance, which since has completed 50 projects in seven Western states. This one is the largest and the first commissioned by the Bureau of Reclamation. Tribal leaders and state and federal wildlife officials have been working for two decades to restore the fishery in Pyramid Lake ‚Äì a remnant of ancient Lake Lahontan, an inland sea that covered 8,450 square miles of western Nevada during the Ice Age. The trout was thought to have gone extinct in the 1940s and was listed as threatened in 1970. But a remnant population later was discovered in a small brook along the Nevada-Utah border. Cutthroat trout also are native to parts of Oregon, Utah and Wyoming. Tribal Chairman Anthony Sampson said the project is ‚Äúsafeguarding a precious resource of the tribe.‚Äù ‚ÄúWe have to be vigilant to protect and restore what God created for us,‚Äù Sampson said. ‚ÄúEverything we do has an impact on life ‚Äì not just plant life, not just animal life, but all lives.‚Äù

page_description: Tribal Newspaper, based in Toppenish Washington.
message: Elementary school teacher named teacher of the year EUGENE, Ore. (AP) ‚Äì An elementary school teacher in Eugene has been named Oregon‚Äôs 2021 Teacher of the Year, making her the first Bethel School District teacher to win since the award program started in 1955. The Oregon Department of Education Sept. 29 honored Nicole Butler-Hooten, a Siletz woman and an Apache tribal member, The Register-Guard reported. After 14 years working at Irving Elementary, district leaders describe the second-grade teacher as an organized, consistent teacher who leads with compassion and acceptance of students‚Äô cultures. Butler-Hooten identifies strongly with her indigenous lineage, her teaching centers around equity and connecting with families. Superintendent Chris Parra called her a ‚Äúwarm demander,‚Äù which he said is someone who has high expectations for students but pushes them with care. Oregon Department of Education Director Colt Gill and Gov. Kate Brown crashed a Zoom staff meeting to surprise Butler-Hooten with the news. ‚ÄúI just can't wait to keep shining light on topics that are really important for creating more equitable outcomes for our students,‚Äù Butler-Hooten told the newspaper. One teacher is selected for the honor each year from a pool of nominated teachers across the state. The Education Department and the Oregon Lottery sponsors the program. Butler-Hooten will be awarded $5,000, and Irving Elementary also will be awarded $5,000.

message: I am excited to tell you we are launching a new radio show on The Village/ Village Folk Show. Prisms: The Sound of Color Back story: Inspired by #BlackLivesMatter and diversity training offered by Folk Alliance International, I asked Carol Maillard, Dom Flemons Dan Navarro Music and Reggie Harris to jump on a creative zoom call. This phone call is a highlight of the year for me - many thanks to these fine, thoughtful artists that make our world a better, more peaceful place. . And a radio show series is born! Prisms: The Sound of Color is a SiriusXM radio show series that is hosted and curated by African, Latin and Native American roots artists - telling our story through a spectrum of music. Please join me in celebrating the launch with Carol Maillard of Sweet Honey in the Rock as your host and curator. --MarySue Twohy
link_text: Hear inspiring & healing cultural stories through music during a new SiriusXM series
description: Experience an enlightening and culturally rich musical experience as roots artists come together to tell their stories when the new series launches on November 1.

link_text: Arlo Guthrie
description:
Gone Fishing

It‚Äôs been a great 50+ years of being a working entertainer, but I reached the difficult decision that touring and stage shows are no longer possible.  I've cancelled the upcoming shows, and am not accepting offers for new ones. That‚Äôs the short version. For the longer version continue reading‚Ä¶

As a folksinger, I never really thought much about getting older. It seemed to me that I could just continue year after year, decade after decade, singing and playing as I had done for most of my life. As the years went by, it got more difficult to keep touring, but I did it, mostly because I‚Äôd been doing it my entire life. It was the life I knew and loved.

In 2016 on April 1st, April Fools Day, I got really dizzy in the parking lot of the hotel, and started seeing as though I were looking through a kaleidoscope. That evening the show went on as though nothing had happened. I had no idea I‚Äôd just encountered a mini stroke until weeks later, when I was told about it. It didn‚Äôt appear to affect my performance, or my state of being. I continued touring for the next 4 years. 

Then, on Thanksgiving Day 2019 (of all freaking days) it happened again. This time I was on my way to The Church / The Guthrie Center to help out with our annual Thanksgiving Dinner that we hold every year. I had pulled over to fuel up and realized I couldn‚Äôt continue to drive safely, as everything was spinning around, sort of like the old days, but without the help of illegal substances. I was taken to the hospital, and was under evaluation, when I broke out. I had an important gig at Carnegie Hall in New York - The end of an annual series I‚Äôd been doing for decades and it was Sold Out. I had to be there. It was imperative.

The next morning I left the hospital, took the family and headed for New York. And what a show it was! We wrapped up 50 years with a terrific evening with the entire family on stage. I really enjoyed it.

The following day I flew to my home in Sebastian, FL just as I had done for years, this time with the history of Carnegie Hall behind me.  My girlfriend, Marti picked me up at the airport, and we settled into the routine of being on the river I loved. Two nights after arriving home, I awoke in the morning and was lurching from sIde to side. I knew something was wrong, and went to keep a doctors appointment we‚Äôd previously set up. The doc said ‚ÄúYou need to go to the hospital - Now.‚Äù

So, Marti took me to the hospital nearby in Vero Beach.  They kept me there for 3 days, running tests of all kinds, and essentially informed me that I‚Äôd suffered a stroke. This time was more serious, as I‚Äôd lost some ability to walk, and I wondered if if would be able to play music. I spent about a week in a rehab center to re-learn the basics, like walking. I went home after that, and began a regimen of playing guitar, walking‚Ä¶ All the things I would need to continue touring and performing. During the entire time, Marti kept the family and close friends advised as to my progress, and took really great care of me. I needed all the help I could get. And she was there to see it done right. 

By the the time our first shows began in 2020, I was at about at 80% and felt like I was improving. Then the pandemic hit. All the shows we had planned for 2020 were at first, postponed, then rescheduled and finally cancelled. My hopes for a gradual recovery onstage came to an abrupt end. 

Meanwhile, I‚Äôd decided back in 2018 to move from the home in Florida. And just as I‚Äôd returned from our last gig in Tennessee, a buyer appeared, and we had a deal on the table to sell The CrabHouse. I wasn‚Äôt in any shape to go through the intricacies of selling a guitar pick, let alone a home with 30 years of stuff we‚Äôd collected. Marti ended up doing it all. She finalized the deal, and dealt with the stuff that either had to be sold, moved or thrown out.  It was quite a lot. But, through garage sales, online markets, movers and friends, she‚Äôd pretty much emptied the CrabHouse of everything, and we moved into her place about a mile away. 

We were there for a few weeks, before it was safe enough to return to The Farm in Massachusetts. That was in June 2020. Since then we‚Äôve been holed up at The Farm trying to keep out of harms way, and also trying to provide some online entertainment for our friends who were, and continue to be, holed up wherever they are. My band and crew arranged a few short gigs that were filmed at The Church, but when I saw the play-back in the editing room I realized that it was not up to the standards I expected of myself, let alone the expectations that our friends and fans had come to enjoy. 

A folksinger‚Äôs shelf life may be a lot longer than a dancer or an athlete, but at some point, unless you‚Äôre incredibly fortunate or just plain whacko (either one or both) it‚Äôs time to hang up the ‚ÄúGone Fishing‚Äù sign. Going from town to town and doing stage shows, remaining on the road is no longer an option. 

I don‚Äôt remember (truncated)

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: How would you have us, as we are? Or sinking ‚Äòneath the load we bear? ‚Äì James Weldon Johnson, To America Join us in Brooklyn‚Äôs historic Green-Wood Cemetery for a night of performance inspired by the poetry of James Weldon Johnson, who is buried at Green-Wood and best known for his anthem ‚ÄúLift Every Voice and Sing.‚Äù Curated by Death of Classical and Green-Wood, it will blend music, history, literature, and dance into a single sweeping, shuddering cry into the night. Featuring poetry by Weldon Johnson, Langston Hughes and Terrance Hayes; stories from the lives of Margaret Pine, the last enslaved person in New York State, a young drummer boy killed in the Civil War, former NY Governor DeWitt Clinton, and others; and music by The Harlem Chamber Players, violinist Lady Jess, singers Danielle Buonaiuto, Freddie June, Paul Grosvenor and many more talented souls. It is a lament, a love song, a prayer, and a plea to America in a time of deep uncertainty, in remembrance of all that this nation has been, and all that it can be. Join us after the performance for a discussion about the creation of ‚ÄúTo America‚Äù with Liz Player, Executive Director and Artistic Director of The Harlem Chamber Players and Death of Classical Founder and General & Artistic Director Andrew Ousley. Hosted by WQXR‚Äôs James Bennett.
link_text: To America: A Live Performance in Green-Wood Cemetery

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: This third night features Brazilian polymath Badi Assad, who is a guitarist, yes, and‚Ä¶a singer, percussionist, keyboardist, and dancer. Also, on the third night, the possibly cosmic and definitely virtuosic shimmering fire of guitarist and composer Vernon Reid together with multi-instrumentalist Laraaji, perhaps on zither. John Schaefer hosts.
link_text: New York Guitar Festival 2022: Badi Assad, Vernon Reid, and Laraaji

Tune in here on this page at 7pm ET, support the scene and save your FOMO for, umm, everything else in life.

message: For the finale of Death, Sex & Money‚Äòs Audio We Love Fest, join host Anna Sale for a live conversation with Back Issue hosts Tracy Clayton and Josh Gwynn. In their new show, Tracy and Josh share the stories behind some legendary moments in pop culture‚Äîincluding ones that are pretty cringeworthy in hindsight‚Äîand go deep on some of people, shows, and songs that changed us forever. Join the nostalgia party and watch as they share some of the moments from the past that are bringing them joy in a tumultuous year.
link_text: Death Sex & Money‚Äôs Audio We Love Fest: Back Issue

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: 2020 has been an historic year for Native American rights. From the Supreme Court victory in McGirt v. Oklahoma to Washington‚Äôs NFL team finally changing its name, Native Nations and their citizens are celebrating long-awaited gains. At the same time, Indian Country has been hit hard by the coronavirus pandemic, and Native leaders have joined the call to address anti-Black racism in policing, policy, and even within our own communities. Journalist and podcast host Rebecca Nagle (Cherokee), host of the podcast This Land, convenes a group of Native leaders as they discuss U.S. Government policies currently at play, the impact of COVID-19 on their communities, and what‚Äôs at stake for native peoples in this election. Panel guests: Amanda Blackhorse (Din√©) is a social worker, mom and was the lead plaintiff in Blackhorse v. Pro-Football; The lawsuit that challenged the trademark of the Washington football team‚Äôs racist name. Amber Starks (Mvskoke) is a salon owner, a natural hair advocate, and a social media influencer at the intersection of Black liberation and Indigenous sovereignty. Abigail Echo Hawk (Pawnee) is a public health advocate, researcher, and the director of the Urban Indian Health Institute and the Chief Research Officer for the Seattle Indian Health Board.
link_text: History in the Making: Reflections on Contemporary Issues Facing Native Americans

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: Director, TED Fellow and White House Champion of Change Madeline Sayet hosts Patricia Marroquin Norby, Associate Curator of Native American Art at The Met ‚Äî where she is the first-ever full-time curator in the department ‚Äî actor Tanis Parenteau (Billions) and artist Ty Defoe as they discuss Indigenous storytelling ‚Äî the mainstream-ization of the concept, their personal practices, and how adding native narratives can help create a more inclusive, and honest, understanding of country and history.
link_text: First Peoples Week: Telling Our Own Story

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: A rich history of peacekeeping and inter-tribal diplomacy existed in the present-day Northeast United States, and traditions thrived that helped lay the groundwork for what we consider to be American democracy. Our host, Iakowi:he‚Äône‚Äô Oakes, speaks with Kanasaraken Loran Thompson to uncover how a great set of laws and treaties maintained harmony from present day Pennsylvania to Connecticut. Presented in collaboration with the American Indian Community House.
link_text: The Great Law of Peace and Treaties of the Northeast

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: Samantha Crain is a Choctaw singer, songwriter, poet, producer, and musician from Oklahoma. Her genre-spanning discography has been critically acclaimed by media outlets such as Rolling Stone, SPIN, Paste, No Depression, NPR, PRI, The Guardian, NME, Uncut, and others. She has toured with First Aid Kit, Neutral Milk Hotel, Lucy Rose, The Avett Brothers, The Mountain Goats, Brandi Carlisle, Langhorne Slim and many others.
link_text: Samantha Crain in Performance

This March, she released her second book, Post Colonial Love Poem, described by The New York Times as ‚Äúno doubt one of the most important poetry releases in years.‚Äù Join Diaz as she shares some of her newest work and takes listener questions.

message: Kai Wright, host of United States of Anxiety, joins Andrea Bernstein, co-host of the Trump, Inc. podcast and author of the New York Times Bestseller AMERICAN OLIGARCHS: The Kushners, The Trumps, and the Marriage of Money and Power, to discuss the tattered state of democracy, the encroaching oligarchy, racism, nativism, voter suppression and how Donald Trump‚Äôs central principle of ‚Äúus‚Äù versus ‚Äúthem‚Äù has infected all of American government.
link_text: Who Matters in America 2020? A Conversation Between Kai Wright and Andrea Bernstein

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: Presented in collaboration with The Lenape Center, host Jocelyn Getgen Kestenbaum is joined by co-directors Brent Michael Davids and Curtis Zunigha. The group will tune in live from Wisconsin and Oklahoma at their respective Lenape nations, who bring home the understanding of diaspora and forced migrations from present-day New York City. Further guests include Lenape Center Executive Director Joe Baker, who will speak to real time work and movements happening in regard to these locations; and Todd Poisson, lead architect of the newly revamped Tammany Hall (which pays homage to the Turtle Clan of the Lenape Tribe) discusses the reopening. The Lenape Center co-director Hadrien Coumans also joins.
link_text: First Peoples Week: Manhattan Is Lenape

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.
message: For almost 50 years, the Nuyorican Poets Cafe has been a vanguard in the world of spoken word poetry and an iconic Lower East Side institution. Now, they join forces with The Greene Space to present a showcase of performers, both established and up-and-coming. This show, hosted by playwright/director Elaine del Valle, brings together poetry, stories and solo work.
link_text: Digital Verse: Nuyorican Poets Cafe x TGS

page_description: Essential conversations and intimate performances, live from New York and heard everywhere on WNYC and WQXR.

The Lenape Center‚Äôs Joe Baker and Hadrien Coumans will lead the blessing. This historically Lenape space has served as an icon in the New York City region for centuries.
link_text: Blessing the New Tammany Hall

message: Staceyann Chin begins her residency in The Greene Space with a conversation exploring what home is for those of us who left home to find ourselves/our voices. How do we carry home with us, how do we find it as we move across borders‚Äîwhat are some of the practices we have to institute in order to find balance/calm/safety?
link_text: Prodigyal: Staceyann Chin and Rachel Cargle in Conversation

message: Get Lit is back in The Greene Space! Join Alison Stewart, host of WNYC‚Äôs All Of It, alongside bestselling author Hernan Diaz and fellow book lovers for this virtual book club event. This month, we‚Äôre reading Diaz‚Äôs TRUST. Alison will talk with a marquee author during a live event in The Greene Space. Until then, follow along as we share our progress on Instagram. This month‚Äôs musical guest is Shaina Taub, singer, songwriter, and creator and composer of the off-Broadway musical SUFFS, which will have just finished its multi-month sold-out run at the Public Theater. The musical stars Taub as Alice Paul and follows the women‚Äôs suffrage movement leading up to the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment. Taub also has a new a new album out, titled Songs of the Great Hill. She joins us for a special performance.
link_text: Get Lit with All Of It: Hernan Diaz

message: World of Outlaws star, David Gravel is making his USAC Silver Crown debut on Sunday the 18th! His debut will be at the Springfield Mile for the 57th Bettenhausen 100. Gravel will be driving the Swanson Encore Team #21. Jeff Swindell is typically the driver of the #21, but he won‚Äôt be Sunday as it will be Mr. David Gravel. Gravel is a Knoxville Nationals champion and made his debut this year behind the wheel of a NASCAR Camping World Truck at Michigan, where he scored a top 10. He currently has six wins the the Outlaw Sprint Cars this year.

message: Justin Grant claimed the 2020 USAC Silver Crown title at the Springfield Mile yesterday (Sunday) afternoon. Consistency was the key for Grant in the shortened 5 race schedule, he may not have captured a win but he finished with 3 top 5's and 4 top 10's. It is Grant's first championship in any of USAC's national series. Kyle Larson led the way with 2 wins on the year. After being away from the series for 8 years he won in both appearances with the series. Those came at the Indiana State Fairgrounds (Hoosier Hundred) and the Illinois State Fairgrounds in Springfield (Bettenhausen 100). Larson has now won on all three-mile races on the USAC Silver Crown schedule, the other being the DuQuoin Mile. Schedule/Results: Selinsgrove Speedway (PA): Shane Cottle Salem Speedway (IN): Kody Swanson Lucas Oil Raceway at Indy (IN): Tanner Swanson Indiana State Fairgrounds (IN): Kyle Larson Illinois State Fairgrounds (IL): Kyle Larson Top 5 Points: Justin Grant: 266 Kody Swanson: 220 (-46) Chris Windom: 212 (-54) Matt Goodnight: 189 (-77) Kyle Robbins: 186 (-80) #dirtracing #kylelarson #usac #silvercrown

description:
A successful first appearance at Tri-City Speedway for the PureMax Racing Oil HART Non-Wing Micro Series presented by EMi - Eagle Motorsports, Schnee, Henchcraft, Stallard has resulted in the addition of two races at the facility later this year. 

The PureMax HART Series presented by EMi will make a return to the track Oct. 23 & 24, during the B-Mod Bash. Both events will be complete shows for points, paying $500 to win and $75 to start. 

There will be a few minor changes to the normal PureMax HART Series presented by EMi format, which will include a 16 car starting field. 

For more information and a complete story, follow this link:
